@book{Planos2012,
abstract = {As a result of the work carried out for the Second National Communication to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, the book Impact of Climate Change and Adaptation Measures in Cuba was published under the AMA Editorial stamp, which integrates the scientific results of rigor provided by 127 researchers, professors and professionals from 27 institutions and organizations in the country. The work, in its nine chapters of technical content, updates and brings knowledge about the changes observed in the climate of Cuba; it presents the most probable climatic scenarios for 2050 and 2100, and on this basis evaluates and characterizes the current status of a group of socioeconomic sectors and natural resources prioritized for the country; It develops the hydrological and oceanographic scenarios that, together with the climatic ones, allowed to determine the impacts of climate change on the sectors and natural resources addressed, and propose adaptation measures. The chapters of the book are: 1. Introduction; 2. Cuba: geography, economy and society; 3. Variations and changes in the climate; 4. Climate scenarios; 5. Water resources; 6. Coastal areas and marine resources; 7). Biological Diversity; 8). Forests; 9. Farming; 10. Human settlements and land use; and 11. Human health. The work offers a perspective of the future and certain policy options to solve the problems that result from the impact of climate change. Likewise, the work identifies information and knowledge gaps; suggests possible ways of acting of the actors in relation to the integration and interconnection of socio-economic sectors with a view to developing and implementing policies and for the creation of new and improved capacities. The relevant aspects of the book's content are summarized below. Variations and changes in the weather; impact on potential water availability At present, the climate of Cuba has a similar status to that projected by the IPCC for an intensified greenhouse effect in the Earth's atmosphere. With respect to the baseline 1961-1990, there is an increase of 0.9 {\textordmasculine}C for the average surface temperature of the air; an increase of 1.9 ° C in the average minimum temperature; a significant reduction of the diurnal temperature range; a higher frequency of prolonged and severe droughts, especially in the summer; an increase in heavy rainfall in winter; and a 10{\%} reduction in annual rainfall. Likewise, there has been an increase in the temperatures of the sea surface and the lower layer of the troposphere. The variation in the rainfall regime has implied a progressive reduction of the available potential water resources. The reduction in the potential availability of water is strongly reflected in the decrease in the volume of usable water, as a consequence not only of the reduction of precipitation, but also because of the increase in competition for water between ecosystems and human demand Future climatic, hydrological and coastal marine scenarios Using the PRECIS Regional Model, with a resolution between 50 km2 and 25 km2, the climate of the future is represented with a high concordance index in the projections for temperature and precipitation. The climatic scenarios considered most probable for Cuba express that the average air temperature can increase between 2.6 {\textordmasculine}C and 4.5 {\textordmasculine}C, and the annual rainfall could decrease between 15{\%} and 60{\%} with respect to the current values. In one of the most favorable climatic scenarios in relation to water, its potential availability in 2100 could be reduced to 24 km3, that is, 37{\%} less if compared to the baseline 1961-1990. In any of the most likely climatic scenarios, the water balance demonstrates a significant reduction in potential water. The Cuban insular platform, and the way in which the seas adjacent to Cuba are related to the ocean, will undergo significant changes; among these: the gradual modification of the physico-geographical, hydrographic and hydroclimatic characteristics of the insular platform and the coastline; the considerable reduction of the low areas of the archipelago and the disappearance of keys; the increase in tidal fluctuations and non-periodic variations in sea level, which will increase during severe atmospheric events; the retreat of the coast to a maximum of 7 km and the alteration in the spatial distribution of the sediments. This coastal marine scenario, combined with the reduction of precipitation, will reinforce the potential freshwater availability deficit because of the impact it will have on marine intrusion into coastal aquifers. A probable scenario in these aquifers by 2100, maintaining the current exploitation regime, reflects that with an increase in the average sea level up to 85 cm and a 25{\%} reduction in rainfall during the wet period, saline intrusion in the direction horizontally it would advance between 4 km and 5 km, while in the vertical sense an ascent would be expected between 19 m and 21 m. This situation would imply a significant reduction in the delivery of groundwater and, in low-powered coastal aquifers, it could represent their disappearance due to the definitive salinization of their reserves. Impacts of climate change and adaptation As evidenced in future water scenarios, the water resources sector will be one of the most severely affected, which will have a very large implication in other resources and sectors. Given the manifest changes in the climate, this sector is already under great stress. The current tension in water management will increase in the future and will be more difficult, even solving the main problems facing this sector in the present. The basis for a better adaptation in this sector is required: the detailed reassessment of the volume of usable water; the reassessment of the hydrology of existing hydraulic works; the revitalization of a hydraulic system with many years of exploitation; adequate de