@techreport{Allaberdiyev2010,
abstract = {The problem of climate change in Turkmenistan is one of the most pressing environmental problems due to the geographical location of the country. Turkmenistan is one of the countries of Central Asia, the second largest by area, located in the southwestern part of the region in the desert zone, north of the Kopetdag ridge of the Turkmen-Khorasan mountain system , between the Caspian Sea in the west and the Amu Darya River in the east. Turkmenistan is characterized by a sharply continental and exceptionally dry climate. The average annual amplitude of air temperature varies between 21-34{\textordmasculine}С. The absolute minimum of air temperature is -36.0{\textordmasculine}С, the absolute maximum + 50.1{\textordmasculine}С. As for many other countries, climate change is a problem in Turkmenistan too. The main indicators of climate change are temperature and precipitation. The relationship between changes in key climate indicators (air temperature and precipitation) with phenomena such as regional drought is studied sporadically and it is difficult to draw certain conclusions. We analyzed the trends in temperature and precipitation (monthly, seasonal, average annual) for 25 hydrometeorological stations as of 2020, 2040, 2060, 2080, 2100 using the MAGICC / SCENGEN software package. The Second National Communications of Turkmenistan will present greenhouse gas inventories, information on climate change policies and measures, forecasts of greenhouse gas emissions, assessments of vulnerability to climate change and adaptability, as well as an assessment of mitigation measures and a number of other topics.},
