@article{Coppola2020,
abstract = {The paper shows the first of this size ensemble of regional climate model (RCM) projections for Europe completed within the EURO-CORDEX coordinated projects. The projections are available for two climate scenarios the RCP2.6 (22) and RCP8.5 (55 members) at a 0.11degree resolution from 11 RCM driven by 8 GCMs. The regional ensemble results are compared with the driving CMIP5 global models but also with the last generation CMIP6 global models. Maximum warming is projected by all the 3 ensembles in Northern Europe in winter, associated with maximum precipitation increase; the opposite is happening in summer with the maximum warming in the Mediterranean and Southern European regions associated with maximum precipitation decrease. The CMIP6 ensemble projects the highest values of warming with the highest spread and highest precipitation increase and decrease while the EURO-CORDEX warms the least and has lower precipitation maxima and minimum but with increased spatial details on complex topography, along the coasts and islands and a more accurate land-sea contrast. There is a high inter model consensus among all the ensemble for increase of extreme precipitation with maximum 15{\%} spread in the Mediterranean region, and increase of drought frequency in the Mediterranean. Extreme temperature indices project increase of heat extremes and decrease of cold extreme with the analogous behavior of the 3 ensembles as for temperature e.g CMIP6 showing the highest values and EURO-CORDEX revealing the most details. With such RCM-GCM ensembles, information can be provided on climate projections and quantification of the signal spread both being quite important for climate services and climate impact community.},
