@article{Pichelli2021,
abstract = {This paper presents the first multi-model ensemble of 10-year, kilometer-scale regional climate model scenario simulations downscaled from selected CMIP5 GCM projections over historical and end of century time slices. The technique is to first downscale the CMIP5 GCM projections to an intermediate 12-25 km resolution using regional models, then these are used to downscale further to kilometer scale. The aim is to provide an overview of projected precipitation changes over the greater Alpine domain within a Coordinated Regional Climate downscaling Experiment Flagship Pilot Study (CORDEX-FPS) tasked with investigating convective processes at the kilometer scale. An ensemble of 12 simulations, performed by different research groups around Europe, is analysed. The key characteristic of the model members of the ensemble is to work at a resolution allowing for explicit treatment of convective processes ({\~{}}3km). The simulations are evaluated through comparison with high resolution observations while the complementary ensemble of 12-25 km resolution driving models is used as a benchmark to evaluate the added value of “convection-permitting” ensemble. The results show that the kilometer-scale ensemble is able to improve the representation of fine scale details of mean daily, wet-day/hour frequency, wet- day/hour intensity and heavy precipitation on a seasonal scale. It also improves the onset and peak of the summer diurnal convection. The kilometer-scale ensemble refines and enhances the projected patterns of change from coarser resolution simulations and even modifies the sign of the daily precipitation intensity change and heavy precipitation over some regions. They also show a bigger amplitude of change for the diurnal cycle for mean, intensity, frequency and extreme and a larger positive change for high to extreme events for both daily and hourly precipitation distribution. The results are encouraging and the use of such ensembles at the convection resolving scale represents an exciting way forward for robust assessment of the local impacts of future climate change.},
